# Chan Tam Hoi @ Paul Chan _v_ Tang Swea Phing and another  

### \[2022\] SGDC 95

Tort – Defamation – Publication

Tort – Defamation – Justification

Tort – Defamation – Damages

27 May 2022 - Judgment reserved.

### District Judge Ng Tee Tze Allen:

1       In this action, Mr Paul Chan, the plaintiff, sued Ms Tang Swea Phing, the 1st defendant, and SDCS Holdings Pte Ltd, the 2nd defendant, (collectively, the “**defendants**”) for defamation. He alleged that the 1st defendant had engaged the 2nd defendant to recover an alleged debt of S$120,000 from him, and that the 2nd defendant had defamed him in the course of doing so. He sought damages to be assessed and a permanent injunction to restrain the defendants from further defaming him.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1)

2       The defendants accepted that the 2nd defendant was engaged to recover the alleged debt for the 1st defendant and that it tried to do so. However, they disagreed that the plaintiff was defamed. They also asserted that the defence of justification applied because the plaintiff did in fact owe the 1st defendant S$120,000. On this basis, the 1st defendant made a counterclaim for S$120,000 against the plaintiff.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2)

3       Having considered the evidence and the parties’ submissions, I find in favour of the plaintiff. I award damages to the sum of S$10,000 to him. However, I decline to grant the injunction. I also dismiss the 1st defendant’s counterclaim. My reasons are as follows.

## Facts

### The relationship between the plaintiff and the 1st defendant

4       The plaintiff is the sole director and majority shareholder of NSC Capital Pte Ltd (“**NSC**”). He is also the sole director and shareholder of Menon Network Pte Ltd (“**Menon Network**”).[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) NSC and Menon Network (collectively, the “**Companies**”) were sister companies which shared the same office premise at 152 Beach Road #28-05 Gateway East Singapore 189721.[^4]

5       The 1st defendant was employed until August 2017.[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5) In the course of her work, she managed the accounts of both Companies.[^6]

6       It was clear that the plaintiff and the 1st defendant had a good relationship initially:

> (a)     In his affidavit of evidence in chief (“**AEIC**”), the plaintiff described the 1st defendant as, amongst other things, “an ideal candidate” to succeed him.[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7)

> (b)     During cross-examination, the 1st defendant stated that she treated the plaintiff like her father.[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8) Indeed, it was likely for this reason that the 1st defendant extended the loans that form the subject matter of this action.

> (c)     The 1st defendant’s husband’s company, Computercity Systems Private Limited (“**Computercity**”), also did business with the Companies. It supplied computers and other equipment to the Companies.[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9)

### The Alleged Debt of S$120,000

7       A key dispute in this action was whether the plaintiff personally owed the 1st defendant the sum of S$120,000 (the “**Alleged Debt**”). The Alleged Debt comprised: (a) an alleged loan of S$20,000 (the “**S$20k Loan**”) and (b) an alleged loan of S$100,000 (the “**S$100k Loan**”).

#### The S$20k Loan

8       The S$20k Loan was made when the Companies were facing cash flow issues in or around October 2016. They were unable to pay the salaries of their employees and this led to the 1st defendant transferring a total of S$18,050 to eight of the Companies’ employees on or around 28 October 2016.[\[note: 10\]](#Ftn_10) The breakdown of the S$18,050 is set out in the table below:

9       The 1st defendant added an additional S$2,000 to the S$18,050.[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11) This S$2,000 represented her own October 2016 salary which has not been paid. The plaintiff does not dispute that the 1st defendant was not paid her October 2016 salary.[^12]

10     Even though S$18,050 and S$2,000 adds up to S$20,050, the 1st defendant claimed only S$20,000 from the plaintiff. For this reason, I refer to this as the “S$20k Loan”. The plaintiff’s position is that the S$20k Loan was extended to the Companies, and not to him personally.[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13)

#### The S$100k Loan

11     The S$100k Loan was made on or around 3 November 2016. On that day, the 1st defendant transferred S$100,000 to NSC’s UOB Account No. XXX. The money was used to pay for the Companies’ office rent.[\[note: 14\]](#Ftn_14) The 1st defendant’s case is that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff.[^15] The plaintiff’s case is that the S$100k Loan was extended to the Companies.[^16]

## The 2nd defendant sought to recover S$120,000 for the 1st defendant

12     It is common ground that the 1st defendant was not repaid the Alleged Debt and that the 1st defendant engaged the 2nd defendant to recover the same from the plaintiff on 11 March 2019.[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17)

13     It is also common ground that the 2nd defendant made six recovery attempts. The first attempt was made on the day of the 2nd defendant’s engagement itself (“**Attempt 1**”). On 11 March 2019, the 2nd defendant sent a letter to the Companies’ mailbox. The letter was addressed to the plaintiff. Amongst other things, it demanded payment of the S$120,000 and stated that “\[f\]ailure to respond … by paying the debt amount as stated within 7 days will require us to utilise one of the enforcement options against you.”[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18)

14     The 2nd defendant did not wait for seven days before utilising its “enforcement options”. One day later on 12 March 2019, the 2nd defendant’s representatives attended at the Companies’ premises to recover the Alleged Debt (“**Attempt 2**”). This was followed by two further attempts at the plaintiff’s home on 14 March 2019 (“**Attempt 3**”) and 21 March 2019 (“**Attempt 4**”).[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19)

15     On 22 March 2019, the plaintiff’s solicitors sent two letters of demand (the “**D&N’s letters**”). One to the 1st defendant and the other to the 2nd defendant. Broadly, the D&N letters demanded: (a) that the defendants immediately cease and desist from making and/or causing unfounded harassment and/or allegations against the plaintiff and/or his family members and/or the Companies, and (b) for all supporting documents that substantiated the Alleged Debt.[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20)

16     However, this was to no avail. A fifth attempt was made on 28 March 2019 at the office of Her Velvet Vase Pte Ltd where the plaintiff’s wife and daughter worked (“**Attempt 5**”). A final attempt was made at the plaintiff’s home on 1 April 2019 (“**Attempt 6**”).[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21)

17     On 9 May 2019, the plaintiff started this action.

## Parties’ cases

18     The plaintiff’s case was that the 2nd defendant had defamed him in Attempts 1-6[\[note: 22\]](#Ftn_22) and that the 1st defendant was also liable because the 2nd defendant was acting as her agent.[^23] It was also his position that the S$20k Loan and S$100k Loan were extended to the Companies and not to him personally.[^24] He sought damages of S$60,000 (i.e. S$10,000 for each Attempt),[^25] and an injunction to enjoin the defendants from further acts of defamation.[^26]

19     The 1st defendant’s case was that the plaintiff did not establish a _prima facie_ case of defamation because he failed to prove that any defamatory words were published to third parties.[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27) It was also her case that the defence of justification applied because both the S$20k Loan and the S$100k Loan were extended to the plaintiff personally. She made a counterclaim for S$120,000.[^28]

20     The 2nd defendant also took the position that there was no publication of any defamatory words,[\[note: 29\]](#Ftn_29) and that the defence of justification applied.[^30] It also submitted that the plaintiff had no basis to sue it because it was in the business of debt recovery and had only proceeded with the debt recovery after being retained by the 1st defendant, that it had proceeded with the debt recovery within the bounds of the law, and that it did not have a statutory duty to verify the debt before undertaking the assignment.[^31]

## Issues

21     The following issues arise for determination:

> (a)     Whether the 1st defendant should be liable for the 2nd defendant’s defamatory acts (if any);

> (b)     Whether the 2nd defendant should be liable for defamatory acts (if any) undertaken in the course of its retainer;

> (c)     Whether the plaintiff established a _prima facie_ case of defamation for each of the Attempts;

> (d)     Whether the defendants established the defence of justification by proving that 1st defendant had extended the S$20k Loan and/or the S$100k Loan to the plaintiff;

> (e)     What quantum of damages (if any) should be awarded;

> (f)     Whether a final prohibitory injunction should be made; and

> (g)     Whether the 1st defendant’s counterclaim should be allowed in respect of the S$20k Loan and/or the S$100k Loan.

## Issue 1: Whether the 1st defendant should be held liable for the 2nd defendant’s defamatory acts (if any)

22     In my judgment, the 1st defendant should be held liable for the 2nd defendant’s defamatory acts (if any).

23     It is trite that a principal is liable for the losses caused by his agent’s torts if the wrongful act was specifically authorised. In such cases, the principal has effectively committed the tort himself: Peter Watts, F.M.B Reynolds _Bowstead and Reynolds on Agency_ (19th Ed, 2010) at \[8-177\] and \[8-181\]; _Ong Han Ling v American International Assurance Co Ltd and others_ \[2018\] 5 SLR 54962 at \[208\] and \[210\].

24     In the present case, the plaintiff submitted that the 1st defendant had specifically authorised the 2nd defendant to commit the wrongful acts and as such should be held liable.[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32)

25     The 1st defendant disagreed. She testified that: (a) she did not instruct the 2nd defendant on how to recover the Alleged Debt,[\[note: 33\]](#Ftn_33) (b) she did not know precisely how the 2nd defendant was attempting to recover the Alleged Debt,[^34] and (c) she trusted the 2nd defendant to “stick to legal means in getting the debt back”[^35] and to act in “the right way”.[^36]

26     I find in favour of the plaintiff. In her retainer with the 2nd defendant of 11 March 2019 (the “**retainer**”), the 1st defendant authorised the 2nd defendant “to act on \[her\] behalf to demand S$120,000 … from \[the plaintiff\]”. To that end, she authorised the 2nd defendant to “visit” the plaintiff “5-8 times a month” even though this may “inconvenience” and “embarrass” him. The relevant clauses read:[\[note: 37\]](#Ftn_37)

> 8\. …

> d)     **SDCS will visit debtors 5-8 times a month** and it could be days from Monday to Sunday and our visiting hours are before 10pm only. SDCS will send (1) overall monthly report to the client via email containing the latest photos / video footage of the visits. …

> …

> e)    SDCS administrator shall send to “the client” a copy of LOD (Letter of demand) via email as part of our procedures as this Letter of demand will serve to the debtor/s via normal mail after the case files is done, but before our operations visits them as it states clearly that within 7 days **if debtors \[sic\] fail to make payment, we will send our debt recovery specialists down to visit the debtor and this may cause them inconvenience and embarrassment**.

> …

> (emphasis in bold)

27     Now, assuming that it was defamatory to assert that a person is indebted for a large sum (which I thought it was, see \[47\] below), it was difficult to see how authorising a debt collector to “visit” that person and to permit it to “embarrass” that person would not constitute an express authorisation to defame that person.

28     In any event, the 1st defendant knew what actions the 2nd defendant would take. She testified that: (a) she engaged the 2nd defendant because it could attend at the plaintiff’s house and office on her behalf to recover the Alleged Debt,[\[note: 38\]](#Ftn_38) (b) she provided the 2nd defendant with the details of the plaintiff, his children, and his home,[^39] and (c) she received updates from Ms Balvinda Kaur on Attempt 2,[^40] and by the 2nd defendant itself on Attempts 2 and 3.[^41]

29     Finally, while the 1st defendant pleaded that she had terminated the 2nd defendant’s engagement after receiving D&N’s letter of 22 March 2019,[\[note: 42\]](#Ftn_42) no evidence was adduced to prove this.

## Issue 2: Whether the 2nd defendant should be held liable for defamatory acts undertaken in the course of its retainer with the 1st defendant

30     I turn to the 2nd defendant. The 2nd defendant submitted it should not be sued because: (a) it was in the business of debt recovery and had acted on the 1st defendant’s instructions to recover the Alleged Debt, (b) there were WhatsApp messages that supported the 1st defendant’s version of events, (c) it did not have a statutory duty to verify the debt before undertaking the assignment, and (d) it acted within the bounds of the law.[\[note: 43\]](#Ftn_43)

31     I was unable to accept these submissions.

32     First, the 2nd defendant’s engagement by the 1st defendant was not a defence. The general rule is that a person who commits a tort under the authority, instructions, or orders of another remains personally liable for the tort. The fact that he acted as an agent is not a defence: Peter Watts, F.M.B Reynolds _Bowstead and Reynolds on Agency_ (19th Ed, 2010) at \[9-115\]-\[9-116\]. In the present case, no basis was identified to explain why this general rule should not apply. And I could not see why it should not. The 2nd defendant was being paid for an assignment which it knew may cause the plaintiff “inconvenience and embarrassment” (see \[26\] above).

33     I turn to the 2nd defendant’s point that it had proceeded with the debt recovery because there were WhatsApp messages which supported the 1st defendant’s version of events. I agree that the 2nd defendant should undertake the necessary due diligence before accepting assignments. Such due diligence would mitigate the risks of it pursuing an innocent party. However, due diligence is not a defence to the tort of defamation. See Gary Chan, _The Law of Torts in Singapore_ (2 Ed, 2016) (Academy Publishing) at \[13.001\] which lists the defences to defamation.

34     Third, the 2nd defendant’s submission that it did not have a statutory duty to verify the Alleged Debt did not assist it given that the plaintiff was not suing for breach of statutory duty.

35     Finally, it was not clear what the 2nd defendant meant by its submission that it had proceeded with the debt recovery within the bounds of the law. Assuming the 2nd defendant’s point was that it had not breached any criminal laws, that was neither here nor there. This was a civil suit, not a criminal one. Assuming the 2nd defendant’s point was that it had not defamed the plaintiff, this is the subject matter of this action and which I turn to.

## Issue 3: Whether the plaintiff established a prima facie case of defamation

36     The elements to establish a _prima facie_ case of defamation was not in dispute. Three elements had to be proved:

> (a)     the statement(s) in question had to be defamatory. This would be the case if the statement(s) in question lowers the plaintiff in the estimation of right-thinking members of society generally, causes the plaintiff to be shunned or avoided, or exposes the plaintiff to hatred, contempt or ridicule;

> (b)     the statement(s) had to be published to a third party; and

> (c)     the statement(s) must refer to the plaintiff.

See _Golden Season Pte Ltd v Kairos Singapore Holdings Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 2 SLR 751</span> at \[35\]-\[36\].

37     I turn to consider whether these elements were established.

### Attempt 1: The 11 March 2019 letter

38     In Attempt 1, the 2nd defendant sent a letter dated 11 March 2019. The letter was addressed to the plaintiff and demanded that he pay the Alleged Debt. The key portions of the 11 March 2019 letter read:[\[note: 44\]](#Ftn_44)

> 
| 

DATE

 | 

: 11 MARCH 2019

 |
| 

OUR REF

 | 

: (SDCS 19067)

 |
| 

TO

 | 

: PAUL CHAN

 |
| 

ADDRESS

 | 

: 152 BEACH ROAD LEVEL 28 GATEWAY EAST SINGAPORE 189721

 |
| 

**LETTER OF DEMAND**

 |
| 

Dear Sir/Madam

We act on behalf of **TANG SWEA PHING** (Our client) to demand the said amount (**$120,000**) that you are indebted / owed to our client which you are fully aware of.

This is the **FINAL REMINDER** prior to taking further action against you. Failure to respond to this notice by paying the debt amount as stated within 7 days will require us to utilise one of the enforcement options against you. No further notice will be given prior to further enforcement actions.

If you fail to pay within the deadline set out herein, our **DEBT ENFORCEMENT TEAM** will personally call on you to demand payment and proceed with house visit.

…

Yours faithfully

SDCS HOLDINGS PTE LTD

 |

  
  

39     I accept that the 11 March 2019 letter was defamatory and that it referred to the plaintiff. However, I was unable to allow the plaintiff’s defamation claim as he failed to plead the fact of publication. I explain.

40     It is trite that a claimant must plead all material facts so that his opponent is put on guard and is aware of the case to meet. In this respect, “material facts” refer to all facts necessary to formulate a complete cause of action: Singapore Civil Procedure 2021 Volume 1 (Singapore Sweet & Maxwell, London Sweet & Maxwell) (“**Singapore Civil Procedure**”) at \[18/7/12\].

41     In the present case, the plaintiff referred to the 11 March 2019 letter in only \[6\] of his SOC, and nothing is said about this letter being published:[\[note: 45\]](#Ftn_45)

> 6.    By way of a letter of demand issued from the 2nd Defendant to the Plaintiff dated 11 March 2019, the Plaintiff was informed that the 1st Defendant had engaged the services of the 2nd Defendant to demand for the said amount of S$120,000 that is allegedly indebted by the Plaintiff to the 1st Defendant (“**Alleged Debt**”).

42     The plaintiff’s SOC also made clear that he was not asserting that the issuance of the 11 March 2019 letter was defamatory. The 11 March 2019 letter and the aforesaid SOC \[6\] is not found in the section which the plaintiff devoted to the alleged defamatory words. That section is titled “II. The Defamatory Words”. It spanned from \[7\] to \[12\] and detailed only Attempts 2-6.

43     In my judgment, this is not a case where the defendants could be compensated adequately with costs if the plaintiff were permitted to deviate from his pleaded case: _Noor Azlin bte Abdul Rahman v Changi General Hospital Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGCA 111</span> at \[274\]. The plaintiff sued for defamation in only Attempts 2-6 till the eve of trial. In his opening statement, the plaintiff stated that his case was “that an ordinary person would find the Words in paragraphs \[7\] to \[12\] of the Statement of Claim defamatory”.[^46] As such, permitting the plaintiff to deviate from his pleaded case would prejudice the defendants irremediably. It would take the defendants by surprise and deprive them of the opportunity to dispute the elements of the tort and/or raise the necessary defences.[^47]

44     In any event, the evidence did not support the finding that the 11 March 2019 letter was published to Ms Balvinda Kaur. Ms Kaur testified that the 11 March 2019 letter was in a “normal DL envelop”[\[note: 48\]](#Ftn_48) and that she “didn’t open the content of the letter and read it or anything.”[^49] In any event, even if she read the letter when it was delivered, it is not clear why publication would be established. In _Huth v Huth_ <span class="citation">\[1915\] 3 KB 32</span> the Court held that publication was not established when a butler who was not under a duty to open defamatory letters sent by the defendants to the plaintiffs did so. In the present case, there was no evidence that Ms Kaur had a duty to open and read the 11 March 2019 letter.

### Attempt 2: The first red letter

45     Attempt 2 took place on 12 March 2019. The 2nd defendant’s representatives attended at the Companies’ office to demand repayment of the Alleged Debt.[\[note: 50\]](#Ftn_50) They placed a standee outside the office which stated _inter alia_ “DEBT COLLECTION IN PROGRESS” and demanded to speak with the plaintiff. The plaintiff did not meet them. As such, they spoke to Ms Balvinda Kaur and handed her the **first red letter**. The key parts read:[^51]

> 
| 

**Debtor Name:** Paul

 | 

**Customer Name**: Tang Swea Phing

 |
| 

Dear Sir/Madam, we are looking for the Above Person, demanding an amount of SGD120,000.

**PREMISES WE WENT TODAY**

**ADD:** \[ADDRESS\]

Dear Sir/Madam

This is to notify you that payment is past due from the day we sent our “Letter of Demand” to your Premises to inform you of the outstanding which you have owed our Client. Today we have visited you at (6.30).

If you have not settled, please contact our office at the above hotline as soon as possible to make the overdue payment to avoid unnecessary embarrassment and inconvenience. If you have settled the above matter, kindly send us a screenshot of the receipt.

Yours Faithfully

 |

  
  

46     I find that the first red letter referred to the plaintiff as it referred to him by name: _Lee Hsien Loong v Review Publishing Co Ltd and another_ <span class="citation">\[2009\] 1 SLR(R) 177</span> at \[27\].

47     I find also that the first red letter contained defamatory statements. In _Koh Kok Cheng v Vernes Asia Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[1993\] SGHC 23</span> (“**_Koh Kok Cheng_**”), the Court considered a letter of demand which stated that the claimant owed the defendants a substantial sum of money. The Court found the letter of demand defamatory because it suggested that the claimant was unable or unwilling to pay up his debts or is a person who does not fulfil his contractual obligations.

48     In the present case, the plaintiff pleaded that the first red letter meant he was personally indebted to the 1st defendant for the Alleged Debt and that he was unable and/or unwilling to repay the 1st defendant the Alleged Debt.[\[note: 52\]](#Ftn_52) I accept this interpretation. The first red letter stated in no uncertain terms that the plaintiff “_owed_” the 1st defendant S$120,000, which was “_outstanding_” and “_overdue_”. This clearly indicates that the plaintiff was personally indebted for the Alleged Debt and that he was unable or unwilling to pay it.

49     I turn to issue of publication. The plaintiff’s case is that the first red letter was published to Ms Balvinda Kaur. The defendants disagreed, alleging that the first red letter was contained in an envelope. I find in favour of the plaintiff for the following reasons.

50     First, it was clear from Ms Kaur’s evidence that she was handed the first red letter that was not in an envelope. In her AEIC, she described the document that she was “handed” as “a letter issued by \[the 2nd defendant\]” marked “urgent” and “printed on red paper”.[\[note: 53\]](#Ftn_53) This went unrebutted during her cross-examination.[^54]

51     By contrast, the defendants’ evidence that the first red letter was placed in an envelope was weak. The only other witness present at Attempt 2 was Mr Kenneth Tien. However, he said nothing about the alleged envelope in his AEIC[\[note: 55\]](#Ftn_55) and admitted during re-examination that he did not know whether the first red letter was in an envelope.[^56]

52     The furthest Mr Tien went was to testify that it was the 2nd defendant’s practice to place such letters in envelopes.[\[note: 57\]](#Ftn_57) However, the point was not well substantiated. Amongst other things, no evidence was adduced to show whether and, if so, how this “practice” was enforced. Furthermore, the existence of this “practice” was contradicted by the first paragraph of the first red letter (see \[45\] above). That paragraph is addressed to third parties:

> “Dear Sir/Madam, we are looking for the Above Person, demanding an amount of SGD120,000.”

As such, it appeared that the 2nd defendant intended for the first red letter to be read by third parties. If so, the first red letter would not have been delivered in an envelope.

53     For these reasons, I find that the plaintiff has established a _prima facie_ case of defamation in respect of Attempt 2.

### Attempt 3: The second red letter

54     Attempt 3 took place on 14 March 2019 at the plaintiff’s home. In this respect, the plaintiff pleaded at \[9\] of his SOC and the sub-paragraphs which followed that the 2nd defendant’s representatives attended at his home and gave his helper the **second red letter**.[\[note: 58\]](#Ftn_58)

55     The plaintiff’s case is that the second red letter was “identical in appearance and content” to the first red letter (see \[45\]-\[48\] above).[\[note: 59\]](#Ftn_59) This is not contested.[^60] As such, the key issue was whether it was published. Two points were raised in this respect:

> (a)     First, that the plaintiff had failed to prove publication of the second red letter to his helper because she was not called and his evidence was hearsay;[\[note: 61\]](#Ftn_61) and

> (b)     Second, that all “demand letters were placed in envelopes”.[\[note: 62\]](#Ftn_62)

56     I was unable to accept the hearsay point. First, the 2nd defendant admitted that its representatives had handed the second red letter to the plaintiff’s helper in \[6\] of its Defence (Amendment No.1):

> 6.    Save that the 2nd Defendant was at the Plaintiff’s Home, para 9 of the SOC and the sub-paras are denied. The Plaintiff is put to strict proof. The helper was asked if “sir” (i.e. the Plaintiff) was at home and when she said he was not in, **the 2nd Defendant left after handing over the 2nd Red Letter to the helper.** The 2nd Defendant was not aware of the police report.

> (emphasis in bold)

57     Second, as the plaintiff submitted, the burden of establishing publication can be discharged indirectly by an inference that publication must have occurred: _Qingdao Bohai Construction Group Co, Ltd v Goh Teck Beng_ <span class="citation">\[2016\] 4 SLR 977</span> (“**Qingdao**”) at \[38\], \[41\]. In this respect, while the plaintiff was not physically present when the second red letter was handed to his helper, the evidence before me was sufficient for me to draw such an inference. Such evidence includes:

> (a)     The second red letter itself. This letter was annexed to the plaintiff’s AEIC and contained in the Agreed Bundle of Documents. Its existence and authenticity was not disputed.

> (b)     The plaintiff’s testimony in his AEIC that he received the second red letter from his helper.[\[note: 63\]](#Ftn_63) This was a fact within his personal knowledge and it went unrebutted.

Under these circumstances, there was little doubt that the plaintiff had received the second red letter from his helper who in turn had received it from the 2nd defendant’s representatives. Indeed, neither defendant suggested how else the plaintiff’s helper could have obtained it.

58     I turn to the submission that the second red letter was delivered in an envelope. I reject this submission. First, this is a material fact which should have been pleaded pursuant to the Rules of Court 2014, O 18 r 8(1). However, it was not. To the contrary, the 2nd defendant’s pleadings indicated that there was no such envelope (see \[56\] above). Further, this submission was not well supported. The only evidence on the point was Mr Tien’s testimony that it was the 2nd defendant’s “practice” to place such letters in envelopes.[\[note: 64\]](#Ftn_64) However, his evidence on this “practice” fell short and was contradicted by the text of the letters which the 2nd defendant issued (see \[52\] above).

59     Under these circumstances, I find that the second red letter was published to the plaintiff’s helper and that the plaintiff had established a _prima facie_ case of defamation in respect of Attempt 3.

### Attempt 4: Oral demands to repay the debt

60     Attempt 4 took place on 21 March 2019. The plaintiff’s pleaded case is set out at SOC \[10\]. Therein, the plaintiff pleaded that the 2nd defendant’s representative attended at his home when he was not around. Accordingly, the 2nd defendant’s representative banged on his door repeatedly and demanded that the plaintiff repay the Alleged Debt. The plaintiff claimed that the demands were heard by his wife, helper and neighbours.[\[note: 65\]](#Ftn_65)

61     On the authorities at \[46\]-\[47\] above, I find that the words (if said) would have referred to the plaintiff and would have been defamatory.

62     As for the issue of publication, both defendants submitted that the plaintiff failed to prove its pleaded case because his evidence was hearsay. I accept these submissions.

63     First, unlike Attempt 3, neither defendant accepted the fact of publication in their respective defences. To the contrary, and for instance, the 2nd defendant only accepted that its representatives had attended at the plaintiff’s home and knocked on his door. Its 2D Def \[7\] reads:[\[note: 66\]](#Ftn_66)

> 7.    Save that the 2nd Defendant was at the Plaintiff’s Home para 10 of the SOC and the sub-paras are not admitted. The 2nd Defendant’s representative left when nobody responded to the knocking on the door.

64     As such, it must have been clear to the plaintiff that he needed to adduce sufficient evidence to prove his case. However, he did not call witnesses who were present at Attempt 4 (i.e. his wife, helper, and neighbours). Instead, he gave evidence on the point personally despite having no personal knowledge of what happened. Indeed, it was not his case that he heard the alleged banging and shouting over the phone when his wife called.[\[note: 67\]](#Ftn_67)

65     Now, I accept that the plaintiff may have received a call from his wife and the fact of the call is within his personal knowledge. However, to the extent that he was relying on the contents of that call to prove what the 2nd defendant’s representatives had allegedly said, that was hearsay and hence inadmissible. As Jeffrey Pinsler, SC, _Evidence and the Litigation Process_ (7th Ed, 2020) explained at \[4.004\], it is the plaintiff’s wife’s perception that must be assessed and tested in cross examination. It is she who should be giving evidence:

> 4.004 The above principles may be illustrated by the following example. A is charged with robbery. W is called to testify that he was told by Z that he (Z) saw A commit the robbery. This is hearsay evidence because it concerns the truth of facts not directly perceived by W. Z should be called to testify because he has personal knowledge of the facts based on his perception. **It is his perception which must be assessed and tested in cross-examination to determine whether it was accurate.** Furthermore, the court has to be satisfied that Z did not fabricate the information. **Even if Z did not lie and was correct in his perception, W may have misheard or misunderstood Z, in which case W’s evidence would be unreliable. If W is permitted to testify to Z’s statement, the court would be compromised in its ability to effectively assess the value of this evidence.** However, there may be circumstances in which Z’s statement may be admissible pursuant to an exception to the hearsay rule if it is relatively reliable or is the best evidence available.

> (emphasis in bold)

66     For the same reasons, whatever the plaintiff’s helper and/or neighbour(s) told him about what the 2nd defendant’s representative(s) said is also hearsay and inadmissible.[\[note: 68\]](#Ftn_68) Similarly, to the extent that he is relying on the contents of the police reports which he and his wife filed to prove what the 2nd defendant’s representative(s) allegedly said, that is hearsay and inadmissible.

67     Accordingly, the plaintiff’s claim in respect of Attempt 4 is dismissed.

68     I make one final observation on Attempt 4. As the plaintiff was alleging slander, he had to either (a) plead and adduce proof of special damages, or (b) prove that a common law or statutory exception (e.g. s 5 of the Defamation Act (Cap 75)(2014 Rev Ed)) applied. Otherwise, his claim would not be actionable: Gary Chan, _The Law of Torts in Singapore_ (2 Ed, 2016) (Academy Publishing) at \[12.006\]. However, the plaintiff did neither in the present case.

### Attempt 5: The third red letter

69     Attempt 5 took place on 28 March 2019 at the offices of Her Velvet Vase Pte Ltd (“**HVV Office**”) where the plaintiff’s wife and daughter worked. In this respect, the plaintiff pleaded at SOC \[11\] that the 2nd defendants’ representatives slipped a **third red letter** under the HVV Office’s door.[\[note: 69\]](#Ftn_69)

70     The wording of the third red letter was not identical to the first red letter. However, its thrust was the same. It alleged that the plaintiff “owed” the sum of S$120,000 which was “outstanding” and “overdue”:[\[note: 70\]](#Ftn_70)

> Dear Sir/Madam, we went down to your premises to demand an amount of SGD120k.

> DEBTOR NAME: Paul Chan

> PREMISES WE WENT TODAY: \[Blank\]

> This is to notify you that payment is past due from the day we sent out “Letter of Demand” to your Premises to inform you of the outstanding which you have owed our Client. Today we visited You at (\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_).

> If you have not settled, please contact our office at +65 \[NUMBER\] as soon as possible to make the overdue payment to avoid unnecessary embarrassment and inconvenience. If you have settled the above matter, kindly send us a screenshot of the receipt.

> Yours Faithfully,

> …

71     Both defendants did not dispute the contents of the third red letter.[\[note: 71\]](#Ftn_71) As such for the reasons at \[46\]-\[48\] above, I find the third red letter contained defamatory statements and it referred to the plaintiff.

72     However, both defendants disputed its publication on two grounds:

> (a)     First, that the plaintiff’s daughter, Ms Clare Chan, who was called to give evidence on Attempt 5, was not present when the third red letter was slipped under the door;[\[note: 72\]](#Ftn_72) and

> (b)     Second, the third red letter was placed in an envelope.[\[note: 73\]](#Ftn_73)

73     I was unable to accept these submissions.

74     First, even though Ms Chan was not present when the third red letter was delivered, there was no doubt that it was delivered. Indeed, the 2nd defendant admitted that its representatives “appeared at the office premises of HVV and slipped the 3rd Red Letter”.[\[note: 74\]](#Ftn_74) Furthermore, Ms Chan’s unrebutted evidence was that her employees “took a picture … sent it to \[her\] through WhatsApp and then they left it on \[her\] table”[^75] In this respect, the WhatsApp messages exhibited to her AEIC identified these employees to be Ms Serene Du and Mr Vincent Wong.[^76]

75     That said, Ms Chan’s evidence was not without issues. In particular, her testimony that “all the employees at HVV’s Office read the contents of the \[third red letter\]”[\[note: 77\]](#Ftn_77) was a bare assertion. She also admitted that she did not remember how many employees there were at that point.[^78] As such, I could not find that any employee apart from Ms Serene Du and Mr Vincent Wong had seen the third red letter.

76     I turn to submission that the third red letter was in an envelope. The point was not pleaded or established by evidence. The persons who delivered the third red letter was not called as witnesses and the defendants could only rely on the assertion that such a “practice” existed. However, the evidence in this respect was poor. The existence of this alleged practice was not found in any of the AEICs. The defendants could only rely on Mr Tien’s oral evidence of the same. And even then, the point was not well substantiated (see \[52\] above).

77     For these reasons, I find that the plaintiff had established publication of the third red letter to Ms Chan, Ms Serene Du, and Mr Vincent Wong and find that the plaintiff had established a _prima facie_ case in respect of Attempt 5.

### Attempt 6: The fourth red letter

78     Attempt 6 took place on 1 April 2019 at the plaintiff’s home when he was not present.

79     According to the plaintiff, the 2nd defendant’s representative came to his home and started banging on his door. When his helper opened it, the 2nd defendant’s representative demanded to speak with the plaintiff. Apparently, the banging was loud enough to alert a security guard who attended at the plaintiff’s home and asked the 2nd defendant’s representative to leave. As such, the 2nd defendant’s representative handed the **fourth red letter** to the plaintiff’s helper before leaving.

80     The plaintiff’s case is that the contents of the fourth red letter were identical to the first red letter (see \[45\]-\[48\] above).[\[note: 79\]](#Ftn_79) As this was not contested, the key issue was whether the fourth red letter was published. Two points were raised:

> (a)     that the plaintiff failed to prove publication of the fourth red letter to his helper because she was not called and his hearsay;[\[note: 80\]](#Ftn_80)

> (b)     the fourth red letter, like the other letters, was placed in an envelope.[\[note: 81\]](#Ftn_81)

81     Even though the plaintiff’s helper did not give evidence, there was little doubt that the fourth red letter was handed to her. Not only did the 2nd defendant admit to the same in its Defence (Amendment No.1) at \[9\], its Mr Kenneth Tien also stated in his AEIC at \[8\] that the 2nd defendant’s representative had “handed a similar letter of demand” to the plaintiff’s helper. Further, the matters set out at \[9\] above applied equally to the fourth red letter.

82     I reject also the submission that the fourth red letter was placed in an envelope. The evidence was insufficient to make such a finding. In this respect, the matters set out at \[52\] and \[58\] above applied.

83     As such, I find that the plaintiff had established publication of the fourth red letter and a _prima facie_ case of defamation in respect of Attempt 6.

### Conclusion

84     For the reasons above, I find that the plaintiff had established a _prima facie_ case of defamation for Attempts 2, 3, 5 and 6. I turn to the defence of justification.

## Issue 4: Whether the defendants established the defence of justification

85     To succeed in the defence of justification, the defendants had to prove on a balance of probabilities that the allegations made in the red letters are true or substantially true: Defamation Principles and Procedure in Singapore and Malaysia (Doris Chia) (LexisNexis, 2016) at \[7.3\]; Gary Chan, _The Law of Torts in Singapore_ (2 Ed, 2016) (Academy Publishing) at \[13.003\].

86     In the present case, I had accepted the plaintiff’s case that the offending words meant: (a) that the plaintiff was personally indebted to the 1st defendant for the Alleged Debt (i.e. the S$20k Loan and the S$100k Loan); and (b) that the plaintiff was unable and/or unwilling to repay the 1st defendant the Alleged Debt (see \[45\]-\[48\], \[55\], \[71\], and \[80\] above).

87     Both defendants pleaded that the offending words were true in substance and in fact.[\[note: 82\]](#Ftn_82) Here, the parties’ submissions focused solely on whether the Alleged Debt was personally owed by the plaintiff. This was unsurprising given that the plaintiff had not paid the 1st defendant the S$120,000 and was resisting her counterclaim for the Alleged Debt.

88     With these preliminary remarks, I turn to consider whether the S$20k Loan and/or the S$100k Loan were extended to the plaintiff personally.

### Whether the plaintiff was personally indebted to the 1st defendant for the S$20k Loan

89     It is common ground that the S$20k Loan was the sum of: (a) S$18,050 which the 1st defendant had transferred to eight of the Companies’ employees for their October 2016 salary, and (b) S$2,000 which represented her salary for that month. Even though these sums added up to S$20,050, the 1st defendant claimed only S$20,000 (see \[8\]-\[10\] above).

90     The parties do not dispute that the S$20k Loan represented a debt owing to the 1st defendant. The main issue was whether the plaintiff or the Companies was liable for the same.

91     The defendants’ case is that the plaintiff is personally liable. According to the 1st defendant, the plaintiff orally asked her to pay the Companies’ staff’s salaries for the month of October 2016,[\[note: 83\]](#Ftn_83) and agreed to repay the same two weeks later in November 2016.[^84] The defendants submitted that this is supported by:

> (a)     WhatsApp messages exchanged between the plaintiff and the 1st defendant;[\[note: 85\]](#Ftn_85)

> (b)     A letter from NSC dated 15 March 2019 (i.e. 3 days after Attempt 2 on 12 March 2019 which stated, amongst other things that “the company does not have any records that there is an outstanding debt in your favour of SGD120,000”;[\[note: 86\]](#Ftn_86) and

> (c)     The fact that the 1st defendant did not seek reimbursement of the S$20k Loan from the Company even though she did so previously.[\[note: 87\]](#Ftn_87)

92     I did not accept the defendants’ position on the S$20k Loan. The evidence showed on a balance of probabilities that the S$20k Loan was extended to the Companies.

#### Whether the WhatsApp messages proved that the S$20k Loan was extended to the plaintiff

93     I start with the WhatsApp messages. I agree that there were WhatsApp messages which supported the 1st defendant’s case when read in isolation. These messages include:

> (a)     The 1st defendant’s message to the plaintiff of 26 October 2016 where she stated “I will still help u to settle Salary 1st .. 20k”;[\[note: 88\]](#Ftn_88)

> (b)     The 1st defendant’s messages to the plaintiff of 25 October 2018 where she stated “I still hv another 20k+ which i paid in advance of salary. Could u pay me back? …”[\[note: 89\]](#Ftn_89)

> (c)     The 1st defendant’s messages to the plaintiff of 17 December 2018 where she stated “I hv money i lend to u.”[\[note: 90\]](#Ftn_90)

94     However, I did not think that these messages necessarily reflected an intention to extend the S$20k Loan to the plaintiff personally. The 1st defendant was a layperson and these were informal messages. As such, it was unsurprising that there would be some imprecise language. Indeed, the plaintiff’s counsel also identified a number of WhatsApp messages where the 1st defendant indicated that the S$20k Loan was extended to the Companies. For instance, on 15 January 2018, the 1st defendant sent a WhatsApp message stating “I still have almost 150k in company (including my hubby side)”.[\[note: 91\]](#Ftn_91) Similarly, on 5 November 2018, the 1st defendant sent a WhatsApp message stating “i still have additional 20+k owing by NSC / Menon ac…”[^92]

95     Under these circumstances, simply identifying WhatsApp messages which pointed one way or the other was insufficient to resolve the issue. Something more was required. And here, I thought that the WhatsApp messages where the parties discussed how the S$20k Loan would be repaid were revealing because they better reflected whom the parties understood to be ultimately responsible for the S$20k Loan.

96     In this respect, the WhatsApp messages exchanged on 30 March 2017 were particularly instructive. These messages were sent about five months after the S$20k Loan was extended and when the parties were still on good terms—the 1st defendant was only dismissed in August 2017. This meant that the messages were less likely to be influenced by any animosity or the likelihood of litigation. In these messages, the 1st defendant referred to the S$20k Loan, stated that had “not yet claim from company”, and proposed to “gradually claim back the amount”. The plaintiff agreed to this proposal:[\[note: 93\]](#Ftn_93)

> 
| 

1st defendant:

 | 

**Paul .. hope u still aboe to recall . I did sms on 29 nov that above amt not yet claim from company.**

**Can i gradually claim back the amount**

Sept – nsc

Mary – $1960

Joannah-$2200

Balvin – S$2560

Me- $2000

Sept – menon

Faye - $2450

Eileen - $3200

May-$2130

Total-$20100

**Oct - $20100**

 |
| 

Plaintiff:

 | 

**Sure u can claim back gradually beco I dun know how income made next few months**

 |
| 

(emphasis in bold)

 |

  
  

97     I pause at this point to note that the 1st defendant’s reference to a S$20,100 figure in her 30 March 2017 messages was likely a computational error. There was no question that the 30 March 2017 messages was referring to the S$20k Loan.[\[note: 94\]](#Ftn_94) This was confirmed by the 1st defendant’s WhatsApp message of 17 August 2017 which referred to her 30 March 2017 WhatsApp messages and stated that the “Co” owed her “for sept & oct16 salary”.[^95]

98     My conclusion above is fortified by how the 1st defendant pegged repayment of the S$20k Loan to “_when co has money”_,[\[note: 96\]](#Ftn_96) and a potential investment by a Mr Wang Jian in the Companies:

> (a)     On 3 November 2016, the 1st defendant sent a WhatsApp message to the plaintiff stating “I hope wang jian there can get some money for u & u able to repay back all my money .. i still can help u to build all biz & let others investors join in for this round”[\[note: 97\]](#Ftn_97)

> (b)     On 27 March 2018, the 1st defendant sent another WhatsApp message to the plaintiff stating “Hope Wang Jian is coming in soon. Pls keep ur promise to return my 100k plus advance salary amount abt 25k .. Hope ur very genuine Boss” and “Well. If u still need my help.. i will definitely help u..”[\[note: 98\]](#Ftn_98)

#### Whether NSC’s 15 March 2019 letter showed that the S$20k Loan was extended to the plaintiff or the Companies

99     I turn to NSC’s letter of 15 March 2019. This was a letter which NSC sent following Attempt 2. The NSC letter stated amongst other things:[\[note: 99\]](#Ftn_99)

> 3.    The company does not have any records that there is an outstanding debt in your favour of SGD120,000.

100    The defendants submitted that NSC’s letter proved that the S$20k Loan and the S$100k Loan were not extended to the Companies.

101    I was not prepared to make such a finding. The plaintiff explained that the above paragraph was included after a meeting convened following Attempt 2. During the meeting, NSC decided to include the above paragraph because: (a) it was not clear from its accounts why the sum of S$120,000 was due to the 1st defendant, and (b) the 2nd defendant identified the plaintiff as the debtor.[\[note: 100\]](#Ftn_100)

102    I accept the plaintiff’s explanation. (b) is clear from the face of the 11 March 2019 letter and first red letter (see \[38\] and \[45\]).

103    I was also prepared to accept that it was not clear from NCS’s accounts that the Alleged Debt of S$120,000 in general, or the S$20k Loan in particular, was due to the 1st defendant:

> (a)     First, the 11 March 2019 letter and the first red letter (see \[38\] and \[45\]) did not state that the alleged S$120,000 debt was made up of the S$20k Loan and the S$100k Loan. As such, unless the reader was familiar with these transactions, it would have been difficult for him to understand the basis of the S$120,000 debt. However, NSC’s current accountant, Mr Ho Chiman, had not joined the Companies when the S$20k Loan and the S$100k Loan were extended. As I understood it, the person managing NSC’s accounts then was the 1st defendant and she had since left their employment.

> (b)     As such, Mr Ho would have only been able to rely on NCS’s records to ascertain the existence of Alleged Debt. In this respect, it was not clear what records were actually reviewed. However, it was clear from the 1st defendant’s own testimony that the Companies’ records were not in order. Even though she had personally paid the October 2016 salary for the Companies’ staff, she testified that this was not reflected in NSC’s general ledger, and that NSC’s general ledger would instead show that NSC did not pay its staff’s October 2016 salary.[\[note: 101\]](#Ftn_101)

104    Under these circumstances, it would have been unsurprising for NSC to be unable to locate the S$20k Loan or attribute it to the 1st defendant. And as such, I find that NSC’s 15 March 2019 letter did not assist the defendants.

#### Whether the 1st defendant sought reimbursement of the S$20k Loan

105    I turn to the submission that the 1st defendant did not seek repayment of the S$20k Loan from the Company. For the reasons at \[96\]-\[98\], this submission was factually incorrect and I reject it accordingly.

### Whether the plaintiff was personally indebted to the 1st defendant for the S$100k Loan

#### The parties’ cases

106    I turn to the S$100k Loan. There was no dispute that the S$100k Loan represented a debt owing to the 1st defendant. She had transferred this sum into NSC’s bank account on 3 November 2016 and the sum was used to pay the Companies’ office rent (see \[11\] above).

107    The main issue was whether the plaintiff is personally liable for the S$100k Loan or if the Companies were.

108    The defendants submitted that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff and that he is personally liable for the same. Apart from criticising the plaintiff’s evidence, they relied on the following:

> (a)     WhatsApp messages exchanged between the plaintiff and the 1st defendant;[\[note: 102\]](#Ftn_102)

> (b)     NSC’s 15 March 2019 letter which stated that it “does not have any records that there is an outstanding debt in \[the 1st defendant’s favour of SGD120,000”;[\[note: 103\]](#Ftn_103)

> (c)     NSC’s general ledger which reflected in the section titled “Amt due to Directors” a S$100,000 entry which stated “Deposit by SP”;[\[note: 104\]](#Ftn_104) and

> (d)     D&N letters of 22 March 2019 which denied the 1st defendant’s claim for the Alleged Debt because both the plaintiff and NSC “are not aware of any records of the \[Alleged Debt\] in \[the 1st defendant’s favour\]”.[\[note: 105\]](#Ftn_105)

109    The plaintiff disagreed that the S$100k Loan was extended to him. His case was that:[\[note: 106\]](#Ftn_106)

> (a)     the 1st defendant transferred the S$100,000 to NSC on her own accord;[\[note: 107\]](#Ftn_107) and

> (b)     in any event, the parties’ WhatsApp messages and NSC’s ledger supported his position that the S$100k Loan was made to Companies.

#### The plaintiff’s attempt to distance himself from the S$100k Loan

110    I start with the plaintiff’s attempt to distance himself from the S$100k Loan.

111    The plaintiff accepted that he made an initial request for the S$100k Loan. However, he claimed that the request was made on behalf of the Companies and that he had retracted it after the 1st defendant told him that she would have to do so behind her husband’s back. Accordingly, this was why he sent her a message on 28 October 2016 stating “ohhhhh no good”. The relevant messages exchanged are reproduced below:[\[note: 108\]](#Ftn_108)
