![](data:image;base64,)

112    I do not accept the plaintiff’s attempt to distance himself from the S$100k Loan or his supposed concern for the 1st defendant’s relationship with her husband. The messages exchanged three days later belied this attempt.

113    On 31 October 2016, the 1st defendant informed the plaintiff that she would be going to the bank to withdraw the S$100,000 but that “If my husband found out .. sure kill me”. Tellingly, instead of rejecting the money, the plaintiff suggested that the 1st defendant “take it separately”:[\[note: 109\]](#Ftn_109)

![](data:image;base64,)

![](data:image;base64,)

114    Later that day, the 1st defendant informed the plaintiff that her husband had “found out \[she had\] withdraw\[n\] the money” and had told her that “this is steal”. The plaintiff did not reject the money yet again. Instead, he told her “We arrange shares to you tomolo”. In re-examination, he testified that this was “so that \[the 1st defendant’s\] husband will not suspect that she was stealing the money.”[\[note: 110\]](#Ftn_110) The relevant messages read:[^111]

![](data:image;base64,)

115    Quite clearly, the plaintiff had no compunction with the 1st defendant transferring the money into NSC’s bank account behind her husband’s back.

116    That said, this is an insufficient basis to allow the defence of justification. At the end of the day, I was bound by the defendants’ pleaded case. And here, the sole basis raised was that the 1st defendant had extended the S$100k Loan personally to the plaintiff. However, just because the plaintiff wanted the 1st defendant to transfer S100,000 into NSC’s bank account does not mean that he wanted to borrow the money personally. By the same token, just because the 1st defendant trusted the plaintiff and discussed the S$100k Loan with the plaintiff does not mean that she intended to lend him the money personally. Indeed, her message of 28 October 2016 suggested otherwise (see \[111\]). That message read “If my husband transfer 50k to me then I can lend to company”. This brings me to the WhatsApp messages exchanged.

#### Whether the WhatsApp messages proved that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff

117    For the reasons at \[94\] (above), I did not think that generic references to “u” or the “company” proved that the S$100k Loan was extended to either the plaintiff or the Companies. Both the plaintiff and 1st defendant are laypersons who were sending messages in an informal context. As such, some level of imprecision in language is unsurprising. This is apparent from the WhatsApp messages exchanged on 27 and 28 October 2016 reproduced at \[111\] above. While the plaintiff did not say that he was requesting the S$100k Loan on behalf of NSC and/ or Menon Network, the 1st defendant’s reply indicated that she was lending money to one of them.

118    Furthermore, while there were messages which indicated that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff, there were also others that indicated that the S$100k Loan was extended to the NCS and/or Menon Network. Messages that fell within the former category included the 1st defendant’s message of 10 December 2017 where she stated “Another word. U cheated me for 100k. I helped u in sincere but what hv u treated me??”[\[note: 112\]](#Ftn_112) On the same day, she sent a further message stating “Mine is loan to u for paid rental & able to renew.. no my invest”[^113] And again, on 17 December 2018, the 1st defendant stated “I hv money i lend to u. My solution is u can gradually pay some money to me. Let me save it to find new home”.[^114]

119    However, there were also WhatsApp messages that indicated that the S$100k Loan was extended to NSC. These included:

> (a)     The 1st defendant’s attempt on 6 January 2017 to recover the S$100k Loan where both the plaintiff and the 1st defendant proceeded on the basis that NSC was the debtor:

![](data:image;base64,)

> (b)     The 1st defendant’s message of 3 November 2017 where she stated that her husband would not allow her to assist the company financially unless it returns her money:[\[note: 115\]](#Ftn_115)

![](data:image;base64,)

> (c)     The 1st defendant’s message of 16 October 2018 where she described the S$100k Loan as a “loan to company” whilst summarising the events that from October 2016 till October 2018:[\[note: 116\]](#Ftn_116)

![](data:image;base64,)

120    As such, it was important for the defendants to explain why their messages and version should be preferred. After all, the burden of proof rested on them. To that end, the defendants relied on the 1st defendant’s explanation that she only wanted to remind the plaintiff that she was making “a personal loan” and that she “only wanted him to be liable for \[her\] personal loan”.[\[note: 117\]](#Ftn_117)

121    I was unable to accept this explanation. Leaving aside the language used in these WhatsApp messages (see \[119\] above), the 1st defendant had sought to recover the S$100k Loan from NCS on more than one occasion. This included her attempt on 6 January 2017 (see \[119(a)\] above). The 1st defendant also approached NSC’s accountant Mr Ho Chiman and Ms Balvinda Kaur approximately 2 years later to recover the S$100k Loan:

> (a)     The 1st defendant’s attempt to recover the S$100k Loan from NSC through Mr Ho is evident from the WhatsApp messages she sent him on 18 December 2018:[\[note: 118\]](#Ftn_118)

![](data:image;base64,)

> (b)     The 1st defendant also sought Ms Kaur’s help to recover the S$100k Loan from NSC. She asked Ms Kaur to locate the UOB statement which showed the S$100,000 deposit,[\[note: 119\]](#Ftn_119) place the relevant documents before Mr Ho,[^120] and sent chasers to Ms Kaur to find out whether she was “able to check the bank statement”. However, these attempts failed. On 16 January 2019, Ms Kaur informed the 1st defendant that she “already put on the desk for Mr Ho” but that “they didnt say anythn (_sic_)”[^121]

122    In my judgment, the 1st defendant’s attempts to recover the S$100k Loan from NSC undermined her case that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff. These attempts indicated that the S$100k Loan was extended to NSC.

#### Whether NSC’s general ledgers proved that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff

123    I turn to NSC’s general ledger for the year 2016. The general ledger has a section titled “Amt due to Directors”. In that section, there is a S$100,000 entry dated 30 November 2016 described as a “Deposit by SP”.[\[note: 122\]](#Ftn_122) The parties agreed that this entry reflected the S$100k Loan but disagreed as to whether it proved that the 1st defendant made the S$100k Loan to the plaintiff or the NSC.

124    I accept that the entry supported the defendants’ position that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff.[\[note: 123\]](#Ftn_123) On its face, it appeared that the 1st defendant had loaned the money to the plaintiff who in turn loaned it to NSC. However, I did not think that they had proved that this on a balance of probabilities. I explain.

125    First, I was not prepared to take NCS’s accounts at face value because they were not in order. Apart from the matters at \[103(b) above, the 1st defendant testified in trial that there was a curious practice of allowing third parties to include in the general ledger monies under the plaintiff’s account even though they were not directors:[\[note: 124\]](#Ftn_124)

> A:    So, money in their account can be from a third party as long as he gives a direction. So, this practice is allowed. There’s nothing wrong with it.

126    Second, the 1st defendant’s actions belied her testimony that such entries were intended to reflect “the money owed to the person by the director”.[\[note: 125\]](#Ftn_125) As seen at \[121\] above, the 1st defendant had relied on this entry to recover the S$100k Loan from NSC. This supported the plaintiff’s submission that the 1st defendant had included the entry so that she would have proof of her loan to NSC should she need it. Furthermore, the practice described by the 1st defendant was a curious one. In essence, it meant that NCS’s employees were using NSC’s records to document a personal debts owed by one person to another.

127    Third, the evidence was insufficient to establish the existence of the alleged “practice”. The general ledger placed before me was for the period 1 January 2016 to 31 December 2016.[\[note: 126\]](#Ftn_126) And here, no other entry which purported to have this nature was highlighted to me.

128    Finally, even if this practice did exist, it was not clear to me that it applied to the present case. No evidence was adduced to prove that the plaintiff had directed the 1st defendant to make that entry.

#### Whether NSC’s 15 March 2019 Letter proved that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff

129    I turn to NSC’s 15 March 2019 letter. That the letter read:

> 3.    The company does not have any records that there is an outstanding debt in your favour of SGD120,000.

130    For the reasons at \[99\]-\[104\] and \[123\]-\[128\] above, I did not think that NSC’s denial of the debt by reference to its records assisted the defendants.

#### Whether D&N’s letters proved that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff

131    D&N’s letters of 22 March 2019 did not prove that the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff. In paragraph 6 of these letters, the plaintiff’s solicitors denied that the Alleged Debt was owed by the plaintiff or NSC:[\[note: 127\]](#Ftn_127)

> D&N’s letter to the 1st defendant

> 6\. Our client instructs that your claim of the Purported Debt and the engagement of SDCS is wholly unfounded and baseless as he and/or \[NSC\] are not aware of any records of the Purported Debt.

> D&N’s letter to the 2nd defendant

> 6\. Ms Tang’s claim for the Purported Debt as well as her engagement of SDCS to demand for the repayment of the Purported Debt is unfounded and baseless as our client and/or \[NSC\]are not aware of any records of the Purported Debt in Ms Tang’s favour. In this regard, we attach hereto at Tab 2 a letter sent from \[NSC\] to Ms Tang on 15 March 2019 for your reference.

132    Thus, unless the defendants’ case was that the S$100k Loan was extended to Menon Network (which it was not), it was difficult to see how the letters advanced the defendants’ case.

### Conclusion

133    For the reasons above, I find on a balance of probabilities that the S$20k Loan was extended to the Companies, and that the S$100k Loan was extended to NSC. In the circumstances, I reject the defendants’ defence of justification and find that the plaintiff had established a case of defamation in respect of Attempts 2, 3, 5 and 6.

134    I turn to the remedies sought by the plaintiff.

## Issue 5: What quantum of damages should be awarded to the plaintiff

135    The plaintiff sought S$60,000 in general damages for Attempts 1 to 6 on the basis of S$10,000 per Attempt.[\[note: 128\]](#Ftn_128) He did not seek aggravated damages.

136    The function of awarding general damages for defamation is not controversial. They act as a consolation for the distress suffered from the publication of the statement, repair the harm to the victim’s reputation, and serve to vindicate his reputation. To that end the Court may consider the following factors: (a) the nature and gravity of the defamation; (b) the conduct, position and standing of the plaintiff and the defendant; (c) the mode and extent of publication; (d) the conduct of the defendant from the time the defamatory statement is published to the very moment of the verdict; (e) the failure to apologise and retract the defamatory statement; and (f) the presence of malice: _Lim Eng Hock Peter v Lin Jian Wei_ <span class="citation">\[2010\] 4 SLR 357</span> (“**_Peter Lim_**”) at \[3\]-\[7\].

137    The plaintiff submitted that these factors merited a higher quantum of damage and that the award of damages should be increased to deter such further behaviour.

138    The defendants did not contest the general principles above. However, they disagreed as to their application on the facts.

### Nature and gravity of defamation and the plaintiff’s standing

139    I start with the gravity of the defamation.

140    As would be recalled, the plaintiff had alleged, and I had accepted, that the red letters were defamatory because they were understood to mean that the plaintiff was personally indebted to the 1st defendant for the Alleged Debt and that the plaintiff was unable and/or unwilling to repay the 1st defendant the Alleged Debt (see \[45\]-\[48\], \[55\], \[70\]-\[71\], and \[80\] above).

141    In this respect, the Court in _Koh Kok Cheng_ held that such suggestions are not “too serious” because they do not impute dishonesty or fraud. And after accounting for: (a) limited publication in that case, (b) the claimant’s employment as an accountant at the material time, and (c) the defendants’ failure to apologise and attempts to justify what they wrote, the Court awarded S$2,000 to the claimant.

142    The plaintiff sought to distinguish _Koh Kok Cheng_ on the basis that he was a businessman and that the claimant in _Koh Kok Cheng_ was an accountant. He submitted that the injury to his reputation would have been more significant because the defamatory words impugned his creditworthiness and ability to manage his business.[\[note: 129\]](#Ftn_129)

143    Perhaps. However, I was not convinced that he would have been affected more badly than an accountant. Accountants, like businessmen, have professional reputations which may be negatively impacted by the defamatory statement. Indeed, accountants are professionals distinguished by their reliability. As such, the suggestion that they are unable / unwilling to pay up on one’s debt would injure their credit and reputation.

144    Accordingly, I was of the view that _Koh Kok Cheng_ was an appropriate starting point to assess damages.

### Mode and extent of publication

145    In the present case, the plaintiff had established limited publication of the defamatory words. The red letters were published to Ms Balvinda Kaur in Attempt 2 (see \[49\]-\[52\]), the plaintiff’s helper in Attempts 3 and 6 (see \[55\]-\[59\] and \[80\]-\[82\]), as well as the plaintiff’s daughter, Ms Clare Chan and two of her colleagues in Attempt 5 (see \[72\]-\[76\]).

### Conduct of defendants

146    In the present case, I accept that the defendants’ repetition of the libel and the refusal to apologise is relevant: Clerk & Lindsell on Torts (22 Ed, 2018)(Sweet & Maxwell) at \[22-226\].

147    I accept also that there was conduct calculated to add hurt to the plaintiff’s feelings and this should be taken into account: _Lee Hsien Loong v Singapore Democratic Party_ <span class="citation">\[2009\] 1 SLR(R) 642</span> at \[112\]. As a professional debt collector, the 2nd defendant would surely be aware of the impact its actions has on the persons they pursued. In fact, its retainer expressly states that it would send “debt recovery specialists down to visit the debtor and this may cause them inconvenience and embarrassment” (see \[26\] above). In this respect, Attempts 2 and 5 stood out to me.

148    In Attempt 2, the 2nd defendant’s representatives placed a standee at the lift lobby in front of the Companies’ offices that read “DEBT COLLECTION IN PROGRESS”. Thereafter, it publicised Attempt 2 on its Facebook page.

149    I accept that neither the standee nor the Facebook post identified the plaintiff. However, the plaintiff is a shareholder and director of the Companies. As such, he would still experience inconvenience and embarrassment if third parties believed that it was the Companies or their employees being pursued for the Alleged Debt. Here, the plaintiff’s unrebutted evidence was that he was alerted by many people (including his customers) about the Facebook post.[\[note: 130\]](#Ftn_130)

150    That said, the point cannot be taken too far. In particular, I reject the plaintiff’s attempt to analogise the present case with _Liew Wei Yen Ashley v Soh Rui Yong_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGDC 206</span> (“**_Ashley Liew_**”) on the basis that Facebook posts were involved in both cases:

> (a)      _Ashley Liew_ concerned defamatory statements made by one national athlete against another, both of whom were described as national heroes. The defamatory statements impugned the claimant’s integrity, honesty, and honour. And all of the defamatory statements were posted online in the defendant’s blog, Facebook accounts, and as a comment to a Facebook post by the International Fair Play Committee.

> (b)     By contrast, it was not even suggested that any of the parties in the present case are “national heroes”; the defamatory statements in question are not as serious (see \[141\]-\[142\] above); and they were not published online.

151    In Attempt 5, the 2nd defendant’s representatives attended at the HVV office and slipped the third red letter under its door. It is undisputed that the plaintiff did not work there. His wife and daughter did. And in this respect, neither were alleged to be responsible for the Alleged Debt. Notwithstanding, no good reason was given for the attendance at the HVV office in Attempt 5:

> (a)     The 1st defendant asserted that she gave the 2nd defendant the HVV office address because the plaintiff frequented it.[\[note: 131\]](#Ftn_131) However, no evidence was adduced to support this assertion.

> (b)     What I thought came closer to the truth was Mr Kenneth Tien’s testimony that the 2nd defendant wanted to talk to the plaintiff’s family members.[\[note: 132\]](#Ftn_132) But even then, I did not see why there was a need to do so. The plaintiff’s solicitors had already reached out to the 2nd defendant by this point. But this was disregarded because the 2nd defendant believed that debtors would hire lawyers “just to buy time or just want to lie”.[^133]

152    Under these circumstances, I find that Attempt 5 was undertaken to pressure the plaintiff though his family members.

153    As for the 1st defendant, I find for the reasons at \[23\]-\[29\] above that the 1st defendant is equally liable and reject the submission that “she is not in control of the recovery process”. In any event, the 1st defendant has not applied under s 18 of the Defamation Act (Cap 75, 2014 Rev Ed) for a separate assessment of damages.

154    I touch very briefly on Attempts 3, 4 and 6 for completeness. In this respect, the plaintiff asserted that the 2nd defendant’s representatives had attended at his home and harassed his family members and helper. Such conduct should be taken into account if established. However, the evidence before me did not support such a finding. None of the persons present at these attempts were called as witnesses.

### Deterrent effect

155    In _Peter Lim_, the Court of Appeal held that \[8\]-\[9\] that another consideration relevant to general damages is its intended deterrent effect and observed that the effectiveness of the deterrent would depend on the amount of damages awarded. In this respect, the Courts have also observed that while “considerations of deterrence do not sit comfortably with the compensatory nature of damages in a civil action”, they have been accepted as a “practical compromise”: _Lee Hsien Loong v Ngerng Yi Ling Roy_ <span class="citation">\[2016\] 1 SLR 1321</span> at \[22\] and \[23\].

156    I accept that “considerations of deterrence” are relevant in the present case. The risk of defaming innocent parties is inherent in the 2nd defendant’s business model. After all, the 2nd defendant would likely have to act on the instructions of one party without having heard the other party’s side of the story. And the defendants’ retainer demonstrates that they both appreciated this risk. Apart from stating that the 2nd defendant’s visits may embarrass or inconvenience the purported debtors (see \[26\]-\[27\]), the retainer provided a contingency in the event the 1st defendant is found to be wrong:

> 7.    “SDCS” will only act according to the Documentations/Proven Evidence provided by Client and “SDCS” will not be held liable in the event if any of the evidence is not genuine. In the event if this case is not genuine after verification from the debtor and/or the police, SDCS will have to ceased the case immediately and SDCS will not take any responsibilities as we act accordingly to what “the client” declares and provides us. If so, the administrative fees paid upfront by the client, will not be refunded and no commission is needed to pay SDCS for cessation of such cases. “SDCS” will advice Client to lodge a police report if the evidence Client given is not strong enough and “SDCS” will based on the true declaration which client lodge in the Report.

157    In the circumstances, it is crucial that the 2nd defendant act with discretion when executing its assignment. However, it did not for the reasons at \[147\]-\[152\] above.

### Conclusion on damages

158    Bearing the factors above in mind, I was of the view that the general damages to be awarded should exceed S$2,000 which was awarded in _Koh Kok Cheng_. While the defamatory sting was not too serious, the defamatory statements were published on 4 occasions, steps were taken to increase the hurt done to the plaintiff, and this award should include an element of deterrence. Under these circumstances, I assess damages at S$10,000.

## Issue 6: Whether a final prohibitory injunction should be granted

159    It was not controversial that a final injunction may be granted if there are reasons to apprehend that the defendant will repeat the defamatory allegations. Where a defendant has manifested a propensity to repeat the same defamatory allegations against the claimant, it is not right that the claimant should be put to further distress and expense of bringing another action should the defendant repeat the defamation: _Lee Hsien Loong v Roy Ngerng Yi Ling_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] SGHC 230</span> (“**_Lee Hsien Loong_**”) at \[55\].

160    The plaintiff submitted that the defendants manifested a propensity to repeat the defamatory allegations for three main reasons. First, he relied on _Chiam See Tong v Xin Zhang Jiang Restaurant Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[1995\] 1 SLR(R) 856</span> (“**_Chiam See Tong_**”) and _Lee Hsien Loong_, submitting that the defendants in the present case, like defendant(s) in both those cases, disregarded letters of demands by the solicitors. Second, he highlighted Mr Kenneth Tien’s testimony the D&N Letter was immaterial to the 2nd defendant because there are debtors who engage lawyers to buy time and/or lie. Third, he pointed me to the 1st defendant’s evidence that the inconvenience suffered by the plaintiff was of no concern to her because of what he did to her.

161    I did not accept the plaintiff’s submissions that the defendants manifested a propensity to repeat the defamatory allegations.

162    First, I accept that the defendant(s) in _Chiam See Tong_ and _Lee Hsien Loong_ disregarded the letters of demands by the respective claimant(s). However, that was not all that they did. And to the extent that the plaintiff was submitting that ignoring a solicitor’s letter was sufficient for a final prohibitory injunction, I reject it. Consider the two cases:

> (a)      _Chiam See Tong_ concerned an advertisement placed by the defendant which contained a photograph of the claimant. The claimant considered the use of the photograph defamatory and instructed his solicitors to demand that all publication cease. The defendant refused. In this respect, the Court’s description of the defendant’s response is noteworthy. Amongst other things, the Court described the response as “mischievous”, “most offensive” and that it gave the impression that the defendant was “hitting back with a venom”. That was not all. During trial, the defendant’s general manager (who was responsible for the advertisement) remained intransigent and cast aspersions against the plaintiff. Under these circumstances, it was no wonder that the Court concluded that he “did not appear to think he was committing a wrong” and allowed the injunction as prayed.

> (b)     As for _Lee Hsien Loong_, the Court found cause to apprehend further publication for the following reasons. First, even though the defendant in that case had apologised and undertook not to make further allegations, he (i) republished links to articles containing defamatory content, (ii) referred the local and international media to a website that had republished the defamatory article in question, and (iii) posted a video on YouTube and a blog which made further defamatory remarks. Second, even though there was no evidence of further publication since May 2014, he had taken deliberate steps to conceal his actions.

163    The present case is quite different. I accept that the 1st defendant had little regard for any inconvenience caused to the plaintiff. I also accept that the 2nd defendant had disregarded D&N’s letter because of its belief that debtors would hire lawyers “just to buy time or just want to lie”.[\[note: 134\]](#Ftn_134) However, this does not rise to the level as the defendant(s) in _Chiam See Tong_ or _Lee Hsien Long._ Neither responded to D&N’s letter “with venom”, gave undertakings which they breached, or took steps to conceal further publication. And on the facts of the present case, I did not think that their conduct demonstrated any risk of re-publishing the defamatory material.

164    Even though I had ultimately dismissed her defence of justification, I was of the view that the 1st defendant was prepared to have this matter resolved by the court and to respect its decision whatever that decision is. She took much pain to explain why she believed that the plaintiff was personally liable for Alleged Debt and referred me to a number of documents in support of her case. Furthermore, she took no further action to recover the Alleged Debt after filing a counterclaim in this action.

165    I turn to the 2nd defendant. In my judgment, there was even less reason to think that it would continue to pursue the plaintiff. The 2nd defendant undertook Attempts 1 to 6 because of its retainer with the 1st defendant. And in this respect, the retainer was for “a period of one (1) year commencing from 11/3/19”. As of the date of this judgment, more than three years have elapsed from 11 March 2019.[\[note: 135\]](#Ftn_135)

166    Further and in any event, I did not think that the 2nd defendant would continue pursuing the plaintiff for the Alleged Debt even if the retainer remained afoot. I say this for two reasons. First, the 2nd defendant’s scepticism for letters received from debtor’s solicitors stemmed from the view that the underlying debt was real and that debtors were simply lying or buying time. However, we are now past that point. A decision has been made to the contrary. Second, no attempts at recovering the Alleged Debt were taken since the commencement of this action on 9 May 2019. This indicated to me that the 2nd defendant also respected the court’s process and that it would abide by its decision. Indeed, there was nothing to make me think otherwise.

167    For these reasons, I decline to grant the final prohibitory injunction sought.

## Issue 7: The 1st defendant’s counterclaim

168    I turn finally to the 1st defendant’s counterclaim for S$120,000. This claim was premised solely on the assertion that the S$20k Loan and the S$100k Loan was extended to the plaintiff in his personal capacity.

169    For the reasons at \[89\]-\[133\], I find that the S$20k Loan was extended to the Companies, and that the S$100k Loan was extended to NSC. The 1st defendant’s counterclaim is dismissed.

## Conclusion

170    For the reasons above, I find that the defendants had defamed the plaintiff in their attempts to recover the Alleged Debt.

171    I reject the defence of justification and the 1st defendant’s counterclaim for S$120,000. The sole basis raised was that the 1st defendant had extended a loan of S$120,000 to the plaintiff personally. However, the defendants did not prove their case.

172    While the evidence showed that the 1st defendant trusted the plaintiff and that the plaintiff was happy for the 1st defendant to transfer the S$120,000, it indicated that the Alleged Debt was extended to the Companies. Amongst other things, the 1st defendant tried, but failed, to recover the Alleged Debt from the Companies on more than one occasion. In this respect, the defendants had not advanced any alternative basis to ground personal liability (e.g. that the plaintiff had agreed to ensure the Companies return the S$120,000). As such, I make no finding on any such possible alternative basis and reject both the defendants’ defence of justification and the 1st defendant’s counterclaim.

173    The plaintiff’s claim in defamation is allowed. The defendants are to pay the plaintiff S$10,000 in damages. As I did not think that the defendants manifested a propensity to repeat their defamatory allegations, I decline to grant the final prohibitory injunction sought.

174    Costs is to be agreed. If parties are unable to agree on costs, they are to write in with their proposed timelines for written costs submissions. I shall give the necessary directions and fix costs in such an event.
